// libCat SIMD is primarily based upon C++ `std::simd` proposals.
// There are a `cat::simd` and `cat::simd_mask` class whose data
// representations are configured by "abi" info classes.
// These are informed by the following papers:
//
// P1928R2   Data-parallel vector types and operations.
// P0918R1   Parallel algorithms and reductions.
// P2664R11  Subscripting. Permuting subscript and multi-subscript.
// P2876R1   `simd_mask` conversions. Lane bits vs subscripts.
// P3299R1   Unbounded memory. Pointer plus length helpers.
// P3480R1   Lane iterators on `simd` and `simd_mask`, making them ranges.
// P3844R2   Broadcast constructor.
// P3922R1   `simd_mask` unary operators and mask-to-`simd` conversions.
// P2638R0   Intel feedback on `std::simd`.
// P3983R1   Object representation. Array-like layout query trait.
//
// However, SIMD functions are implemented in the form of functors that generate
// masked SIMD forms from unmasked SIMD forms using CRTP. This is inspired by
// the EVE library. For example:
//
//    cat::float4x4 v{1, 4, 9, 16};
//    cat::float4x4 const unmasked = cat::simd_sqrt(v);
//    cat::float4x4 const masked = cat::simd_sqrt[v < 5](v);
//
// The CRTP generates blends automatically, but both masked and unmasked functor
// invocations can be overridden per-ABI by partial template specializations in
// the `cat::simd_abi` namespace. Examples may be found in
// `cat/detail/simd_avx2.hpp`. The core is implemented in
// `cat/detail/simd_ops.hpp`.
//
// `cat::simd_mask` varies immensely between instruction sets, so its data
// representation and truthiness values are determined by partial template
// specializations of a `cat::simd_abi::mask_lane` class. An example may be
// found in `cat/detail/simd_mask_lane_sseavx.hpp`

